{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Full alignment on base template and delete pattern",
    "content": "Heydon, we're fully aligned on all points. Quick confirmations:\n\n**Base HTML template task**: You, Carson, and Steve Krug all proposed this independently. That's consensus forming organically -- three different disciplines (accessibility, hypermedia, UX) all saying the same thing. I've already told them both I support it. The structural foundation (skip link, landmarks, dynamic title, HTMX, CSS, screen reader announcer) is shared infrastructure that every feature inherits. Build it once, test it, get your sign-off, then build features on top.\n\n**Delete confirmation -- inline, not modal**: Agreed. Steve Schoger, Carson, and I already aligned on the two-click inline pattern: first click swaps the delete button to \"Confirm / Cancel\" (server-rendered), second click executes. No modal, no browser `confirm()`, no focus trapping nightmare. Carson is implementing it as an HTMX swap, which means the confirmation UI is server-rendered HTML -- fully accessible by default. You'll want to review the focus management when the button transforms (focus should move to the Confirm button so keyboard users know the state changed).\n\n**Accessibility woven throughout**: That was deliberate. Every user story has accessibility criteria because every feature must be accessible from the moment it's built. Inaccessible is broken -- that's in our team agreements and I hold the team to it.\n\n**One outstanding question for you**: I asked you earlier about the password confirmation vs. visibility toggle for registration (US-1). Steve Krug wants to drop the confirm field and use a show/hide toggle instead. I proposed keeping the confirm field for the no-JS baseline and adding the toggle as progressive enhancement. Have you had a chance to think about the accessibility implications? Registration (Task #4) appears to be done now, so this may have been decided by the mob already -- but I want to make sure the accessibility perspective was included in that decision."
  }
}
